value.value: An action taken to increase the density of a substance and decrease its volume.
An auditory test utilizing the electrical activity of neural impulses to localize the exact site of a pathologic process that causes the hearing loss.

An auditory test performed in children with hearing impairment.  The child is asked to wait and listen for a specific stimulus.  Subsequently, the child responds by performing a motor activity in response to the specific stimulus.
To clear material from the throat or lungs by coughing it up and spitting it out.

label.value: Stage IV Soft Tissue Sarcoma AJCC v7

value.value: Stage IV includes: Any T, Any N, M1, Any G.  M1: Distant metastasis. (AJCC 7th ed.)
A taxonomic phylum within kingdom Bacteria consisting of the Mollicutes, a class of intracellular parasitic bacteria without a cell wall.

A condition associated with mutation(s) in the PPT1 gene, encoding palmitoyl-protein thioesterase 1. The condition is one of a group of genetically heterogeneous neurodegenerative disorders, characterized by accumulation of intracellular lipopigments.
An institution where persons are confined for punishment and to protect the public.
Temporary housing for displaced or at-risk persons.

A condition associated with mutation(s) in the TPP1 gene, encoding tripeptidyl-peptidase- 1. The condition is one of a group of genetically heterogeneous neurodegenerative disorders, characterized by accumulation of intracellular lipopigments.
An inherited disorder affecting mostly males. It results from defective genes that are present on the X chromosome.
An inherited disorder manifested only when two copies of a mutated gene are present.
A temporary, often makeshift shelter for persons displaced by war, political oppression, or for religious beliefs.
Without a stable or permanent residence.
Of or relating to a medical condition or characteristic that is not present at birth but develops subsequently.
A polyp with severe dysplastic features.
A structural chromosomal abnormality caused by the spontaneous or induced breakage of a chromosome. It may result in DNA sequence deletions, chromosomal translocations, or chromosomal inversions.
A file format that is controlled by a private person or organization where the mode of presentation of its data is opaque and its specification is not publicly available.
A published specification for storing digital data that is freely distributed and available to be used and implemented by anyone.
A data format consisting of readable textual material maintained as a sequential file.
A congenital or acquired developmental disorder in which the circumference of the head is smaller than normal for the person's age and sex.
An enzyme-linked serum immunoassay used for the detection of aspergillosis.
A therapeutic procedure based on the inhibition or reduction of the biosynthesis of compounds that cannot break down in the cells.
A worker who travels from place to place as an agricultural worker, ususally moving to participate in harvest activities.
A person who has left his country of residence, and cannot return for fear of human-rights related persecution.
A labeling index evaluating the percentage of cells present in the S-phase fraction. It is used to determine the proliferative activity of tumor cells in a tissue sample.
A germ cell tumor that arises from the ovary and occurs in children.
A fluorescent stain that binds to the cell wall. It is used for the detection of fungi, parasites, and yeasts, using fluorescent microscopy.

A protein that is a member of a structurally diverse group that forms a protein complex which may regulate both DNA repair and the cell cycle. Mutation of any member of this group may inhibit the formation of the complex and is associated with Fanconi anemia.
Fanconi anemia group A protein (1455 aa, ~163 kDa) is encoded by the human FANCA gene. This protein may be involved in both DNA damage repair and cell cycle checkpoint regulation.
The quantity of something that is borne or carried by an individual or population.
Fanconi anemia group B protein (859 aa, ~98 kDa) is encoded by the human FANCB gene. This protein may play a role in both ubiquitination and DNA repair.
Fanconi anemia group C protein (558 aa, ~63 kDa) is encoded by the human FANCC gene. This protein may be involved in DNA cross-link repair and cell cycle checkpoint regulation.

Fanconi anemia group D2 protein (1471 aa, ~166 kDa) is encoded by the human FANCD2 gene. This protein plays a role in chromosome pairing during meiosis, repair of DNA double-strand breaks and cell cycle checkpoint regulation.

label.value: Stage 0 Cutaneous Merkel Cell Carcinoma AJCC v7

value.value: Stage 0 includes: Tis, N0, M0.  Tis: In situ primary tumor.  N0: No regional lymph node metastasis.  M0: No distant metastasis.  (AJCC 7th ed.)
Fanconi anemia group E protein (536 aa, ~59 kDa) is encoded by the human FANCE gene. This protein is involved in the localization of the Fanconi anemia complementation group protein complex.

label.value: Stage I Cutaneous Merkel Cell Carcinoma AJCC v7

value.value: Stage I includes: IA: (T1, pN0, M0) and IB: (T1, cN0, M0).  T1: Primary tumor equal or less than 2 cm in size.  pN0: No regional lymph node metastasis by pathologic examination.  cN0: No regional lymph node metastasis by clinical examination.  M0: No distant metastasis.  (AJCC 7th Ed.)
A finding of acute myelomonocytic leukemia that is not growing and responds to treatment.

label.value: Stage IA Cutaneous Merkel Cell Carcinoma AJCC v7

value.value: Stage IA includes: T1, pN0, M0.  T1: Primary tumor equal or less than 2 cm in size.  pN0: No regional lymph node metastasis by pathologic examination.  M0: No distant metastasis.  (AJCC 7th Ed.)
Fanconi anemia group F protein (374 aa, ~42 kDa) is encoded by the human FANCF gene. This protein may play a role in both cell cycle checkpoint regulation and DNA damage repair.

label.value: Stage IB Cutaneous Merkel Cell Carcinoma AJCC v7

value.value: Stage IB includes: T1, cN0, M0.  T1: Primary tumor equal or less than 2 cm in size.  cN0: No regional lymph node metastasis by clinical examination.  M0: No distant metastasis.  (AJCC 7th Ed.)

label.value: Stage II Cutaneous Merkel Cell Carcinoma AJCC v7

value.value: Stage II includes: IIA: (T2/T3, pN0, M0), IIB: (T2/T3, cN0, M0), and IIC: (T4, N0, M0).  T2: Primary tumor greater than 2 cm but not more than 5 cm in maximum dimension.  T3: Primary tumor over 5 cm in maximum dimension.  T4: Primary tumor invades bone, muscle, fascia, or cartilage.  pN0: No regional lymph node metastasis by pathologic examination.  cN0: No regional lymph node metastasis by clinical examination.  N0: No regional lymph node metastasis.  M0: No distant metastasis.  (AJCC 7th Ed.)

label.value: Stage IIA Cutaneous Merkel Cell Carcinoma AJCC v7

value.value: Stage IIA includes: T2/T3, pN0, M0.  T2: Primary tumor greater than 2 cm but not more than 5 cm in maximum dimension.  T3: Primary tumor over 5 cm in maximum dimension.  pN0: No regional lymph node metastasis by pathologic examination.  M0: No distant metastasis.  (AJCC 7th Ed.)

label.value: Stage IIB Cutaneous Merkel Cell Carcinoma AJCC v7

value.value: Stage IIB includes: T2/T3, cN0, M0.  T2: Primary tumor greater than 2 cm but not more than 5 cm in maximum dimension.  T3: Primary tumor over 5 cm in maximum dimension.  cN0: No regional lymph node metastasis by clinical examination.  M0: No distant metastasis.  (AJCC 7th Ed.)

label.value: Stage IIC Cutaneous Merkel Cell Carcinoma AJCC v7

value.value: Stage IIC includes: T4, N0, M0.  T4: Primary tumor invades bone, muscle, fascia, or cartilage.  N0: No regional lymph node metastasis.  M0: No distant metastasis.  (AJCC 7th Ed.)

label.value: Stage III Cutaneous Merkel Cell Carcinoma AJCC v7

value.value: Stage III includes: IIIA: (Any T, N1a, M0) and IIIB: (Any T, N1b/N2, M0).  N1a: Micrometastasis in regional lymph nodes.  N1b: Macrometastasis in regional lymph nodes.  N2: In transit metastasis.  M0: No distant metastasis.  (AJCC 7th Ed.)

label.value: Stage IIIA Cutaneous Merkel Cell Carcinoma AJCC v7

value.value: Stage IIIA includes: Any T, N1a, M0.  N1a: Micrometastasis in regional lymph nodes.  M0: No distant metastasis.  (AJCC 7th Ed.)

label.value: Stage IIIB Cutaneous Merkel Cell Carcinoma AJCC v7

value.value: Stage IIIB includes: Any T, N1b/N2, M0.  N1b: Macrometastasis in regional lymph nodes.  N2: In transit metastasis.  M0: No distant metastasis.  (AJCC 7th Ed.)
An agent that disrupts the development of an embryo or fetus.
An antiquated term that refers either to nodular lymphocyte predominant Hodgkin lymphoma or to lymphocyte-rich classical Hodgkin lymphoma.
